    management: ["Graves disease treatment options: (1) Antithyroid drugs (methimazole preferred — start 10-30 mg daily; PTU reserved for first trimester pregnancy and thyroid storm); (2) Radioactive iodine (RAI — I-131) ablation — definitive treatment, causes permanent hypothyroidism requiring lifelong levothyroxine; (3) Thyroidectomy — for large goiters, suspicious nodules, moderate-severe ophthalmopathy, or patient preference","Methimazole monitoring: CBC (agranulocytosis risk — 0.1-0.5%; instruct patient to report sore throat and fever immediately), LFTs (hepatotoxicity), TSH/FT4 every 4-6 weeks initially then every 3 months once stable","Hashimoto hypothyroidism: levothyroxine replacement — start dose based on age/weight (1.6 mcg/kg/day for young healthy adults); lower starting dose in elderly and cardiac patients (25-50 mcg/day); titrate by 12.5-25 mcg every 6-8 weeks based on TSH","Beta-blockers for symptomatic control: propranolol (also inhibits T4→T3 conversion) or atenolol for palpitations, tremor, anxiety while awaiting antithyroid drug effect or definitive treatment","Thyroid storm: ICU admission; PTU loading dose (500-1000 mg then 250 mg q4h); potassium iodide (SSKI) 1 hour AFTER PTU (blocks new hormone synthesis before blocking release); propranolol IV; hydrocortisone 100 mg IV q8h (blocks T4→T3 conversion, treats possible relative adrenal insufficiency); cooling for hyperthermia","Subclinical hypothyroidism: treat if TSH >10 or TSH 5-10 with symptoms, positive anti-TPO, or pregnancy planning; observe if asymptomatic with TSH 5-10","Graves ophthalmopathy: selenium supplementation (mild); glucocorticoids, orbital radiation, or teprotumumab (IGF-1R inhibitor — FDA-approved) for moderate-severe; smoking cessation essential"],
